{
  "text": "Leghemoglobin. The leghemoglobin present in the nodule of the plant root was extracted using 200 mg of nodule dry matter, in which the fresh nodules were retired of the plant roots and immediately placed in oven with forced air circulation at 65°C for 72 h. Subsequently, the dry nodules were triturated and incubated with 10 ml of solution with extraction buffer containing KCN at 0.8mM, K 3 Fe(CN) 6 at 0.6mM and NaHCO 3 at 12mM in the proportion of 3:3:4 (v/v) at 30°C by 15 min, after the homogenization it was centrifuged at 10 000 g for 20 min at 4°C. The quantification was carried out at 540 nm in agreement with [CITATION_1] , where human hemoglobin was used as standard.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "84715059"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "84715059": {
      "title": "Determination of leghemoglobin in legume nodules",
      "abstract": "Abstract A method is described for the determination of LHb in legume root nodule tissue. The LHb is extracted with Drabkin's solution and measured colorimetrically as the CMLHb complex on the centrifuged extract. The procedure requires a minimum of specialized equipment and reagents, and is rapid and reproducible."
    }
  }
}